domain_model.plantuml:
@startuml
class System {
  -batteryLife: number
  -uniqueIdentifierCode: string
  +connect(): void
  +displayHeartRate(): void
  +displayBloodPressure(): void
  +displayO2Saturation(): void
  +displayRespirationRate(): void
  +displayVitalsRecord(): void
  +displayRespiratoryWaveForm(): void
  +displayO2SaturationWaveForm(): void
  +displayECG(): void
  +triggerAlarms(): void
  +makeAudibleNoise(): void
  +storeLocally(): void
  +utilizeBattery(): void
  +utilizeExternalPower(): void
  +rechargeBattery(): void
  +sendRecordUpdates(): void
  +shareVitals(): void
  +receiveUpdates(): void
  +continueProcessing(): void
}

class LCD {
  +displayNumericalValues(): void
  +showHeartRateInGreen(): void
  +showBloodPressureInRed(): void
  +showO2SaturationInYellow(): void
  +showRespiratoryRateInTeal(): void
  +showRespiratoryWaveFormInTeal(): void
  +showO2SaturationWaveformInYellow(): void
  +showECGStripInGreen(): void
  +showVitalsRecordInTableFormat(): void
}

class Pod {
  +transferVitalData(): void
  +recordPulse(): void
  +recordPressure(): void
  +recordOximeter(): void
  +recordTelemetryLeads(): void
}

class HospitalPersonnel {
  +defineHeartRateRange(): void
  +defineBloodPressureRange(): void
  +defineO2SaturationRange(): void
  +defineRespirationRateRange(): void
}

class Patient {
  -vitals: VitalsType
}

class PatientRecordsSystem {
  +storeRecords(): void
}

class CentralPatientMonitoringSystem {
  +receiveVitals(): void
}

System *-- LCD : has
System --> Pod : connects to
System --> PatientRecordsSystem : stores records in
System --> CentralPatientMonitoringSystem : shares vitals to
@enduml

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall have LCD that displays numerical values derived from the data acquired at the analog outputs received from the pods.

issues.description: Refers to 'analog outputs' from pods, but REQ-003 mentions '14-Pin connectors' which typically carry digital signals
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether pod data transfer is analog or digital, and specify the data format

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall allow pods to transfer vital data back to the PMS through 14-Pin connectors.

issues.description: Acronym 'PMS' is not defined. Unclear if this refers to Patient Monitoring System
issues.suggested_fix: Define PMS acronym or use full term 'Patient Monitoring System'

issues.description: Conflicts with REQ-004 through REQ-007 which imply separate ports for different pod types
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify if there is one 14-pin connector or multiple dedicated ports

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall have a port for the pod that records pulse.

issues.description: Implies dedicated ports for each pod type, conflicting with REQ-003's single 14-pin connector approach
issues.suggested_fix: Specify exact connector configuration and whether pods can share ports or need dedicated ones

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall allow hospital personnel to define the range of heart rate.

issues.description: Missing details about user interface, data persistence, and access control for range definition
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the interface mechanism (touch screen, web interface, etc.) and where ranges are stored

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The LCD screen shall show the EGG strip in a green color (using hexadecimal color code: #00FF00).

issues.description: Typo: 'EGG strip' should be 'ECG strip' based on REQ-015

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall not make an audible noise when an alarm is not triggered.

issues.description: Redundant requirement - if no alarm is triggered, absence of noise is implicit
issues.suggested_fix: Remove this requirement as it adds no value beyond REQ-030

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system in one-minute intervals, shall send record updates to the Patient Records System database of the field data for heart rate.

issues.description: Term 'field data' is vague and not used consistently throughout requirements
issues.suggested_fix: Use consistent terminology like 'vital signs data' or 'patient data' instead of 'field data'

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall be compatible with Epic EMR.

issues.description: Conflicts with REQ-040 which mentions generic 'Patient Records Systems (EMR)' without specifying Epic
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify if Epic EMR is the only supported system or one of multiple supported EMR systems

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall be compliant with NFPA standards.

issues.description: Too vague - NFPA has many standards, specific standards and compliance criteria not specified
issues.suggested_fix: Specify exact NFPA standards (e.g., NFPA 99 for healthcare facilities) and compliance criteria

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The system shall not receive software updates when connected to a patient.

issues.description: Unclear what 'connected to a patient' means - is it when pods are attached or when actively monitoring?
issues.suggested_fix: Define clearly when system is considered 'connected to a patient' (e.g., when any pod is attached and collecting data)

domain_model_issues.description: Requirements REQ-004 through REQ-007 suggest different types of pods (pulse, pressure, oximeter, telemetry), but model has only generic Pod class
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Create specific pod subclasses: PulsePod, PressurePod, OximeterPod, TelemetryPod

domain_model_issues.description: No class to represent vital signs data structure, yet multiple requirements reference storing and transmitting vital data
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add VitalsData class with attributes for heart rate, blood pressure, O2 saturation, respiration rate, ECG data, and timestamps

domain_model_issues.description: Requirements mention docking station for power and connectivity, but no corresponding class exists
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add DockingStation class with methods for power supply, ethernet connection, and battery charging

domain_model_issues.description: Alarm functionality is referenced in multiple requirements but not modeled as a separate class
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add Alarm class with attributes for alarm thresholds, status, and methods for triggering and silence

domain_model_issues.description: No relationship between System and Patient classes, despite system monitoring patients
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add association relationship between System and Patient with multiplicity 1:1 for 'monitors'

domain_model_issues.description: No relationship showing how hospital personnel interact with system to define ranges
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add association relationship between System and HospitalPersonnel for configuration access

domain_model_issues.description: No attributes to support multiple language requirements
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add languageSettings attribute to System class with supported languages (English, Spanish, French)

domain_model_issues.description: No attributes to store the vital sign ranges defined by hospital personnel
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add vitalRanges attribute or create separate VitalRanges class to store threshold values

domain_model_issues.description: Class lacks specificity for Epic EMR compatibility and data structure for different vital signs
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add attributes for EMR type, connection details, and methods for specific data types (heart rate, blood pressure, etc.)

domain_model_issues.description: Display methods in System class should delegate to LCD class rather than being directly implemented
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Move display logic to LCD class and have System methods call corresponding LCD methods

missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall allow hospital personnel to acknowledge triggered alarms, and shall maintain alarm state until acknowledged. The system shall log all alarm events with timestamp, vital sign values, and acknowledgment details.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model includes triggerAlarms method and requirements specify alarm triggering, but there's no way to acknowledge alarms or manage their lifecycle, which is critical for patient safety in medical monitoring systems.

missing_requirements.description: Low battery warning and battery status monitoring
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall display battery charge level as a percentage on the LCD screen. The system shall trigger a low battery warning when battery level falls below 20%, and a critical battery warning when battery level falls below 10%.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model specifies batteryLife attribute and requirements mention two-hour battery life, but there's no way for users to monitor battery status or receive warnings before the battery dies, which could interrupt patient monitoring.

missing_requirements.description: Pod connection status detection and display
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall detect and display the connection status of each pod (pulse, pressure, oximeter, telemetry leads) on the LCD screen. The system shall trigger an alert when any required pod becomes disconnected.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model shows pods transferring data to the system, but there are no requirements for detecting when pods are disconnected or malfunctioning, which could result in missing critical patient data.

missing_requirements.description: Data sampling rates for vital sign measurements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall sample heart rate data at 1 Hz, blood pressure every 15 seconds, O2 saturation at 1 Hz, and respiration rate at 0.5 Hz. ECG data shall be sampled at 250 Hz minimum.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model shows pods recording different types of data, but requirements don't specify sampling rates, which are critical for accurate medical monitoring and proper data interpretation.

missing_requirements.description: User authentication and authorization for hospital personnel
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall require hospital personnel to authenticate using hospital credentials before allowing access to define vital sign ranges. The system shall support role-based access control with different permission levels for nurses, doctors, and administrators.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model shows HospitalPersonnel can define vital ranges, but there are no requirements for authenticating users or controlling who can modify these critical safety parameters.

missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall allow hospital personnel to assign the unique identifier code to a specific patient through barcode scanning or manual entry. The system shall validate patient identity against the hospital's patient database before monitoring begins.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model specifies uniqueIdentifierCode attribute and Patient class, but requirements don't explain how patients are identified and assigned to the monitoring system, which is essential for proper patient tracking.

missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall perform automatic self-tests of all components (LCD, pods, connectivity, sensors) during startup and every 4 hours during operation. The system shall display self-test results and alert users to any component failures.
missing_requirements.rationale: Medical monitoring systems require regular self-testing to ensure reliability, but no requirements exist for diagnostic procedures, which could lead to undetected component failures affecting patient care.

missing_requirements.description: Respiratory waveform data transmission to EMR
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall send respiratory waveform data updates to the Patient Records System database at one-minute intervals, consistent with other vital sign data transmission requirements.
missing_requirements.rationale: Requirements REQ-041 to REQ-045 specify sending heart rate, blood pressure, O2 saturation, respiration rate, and ECG data to EMR, but respiratory waveform data (which is displayed per REQ-013) is missing from the transmission requirements.

missing_requirements.description: Data storage capacity and overflow handling
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall have minimum storage capacity for 24 hours of all vital sign data. When storage approaches 90% capacity, the system shall automatically delete the oldest data to make room for new data while maintaining the most recent 24 hours.
missing_requirements.rationale: REQ-032 specifies storing 24 hours of data locally, but there's no requirement addressing what happens when storage capacity is exceeded, which could cause data loss or system failures.

missing_requirements.description: Default vital sign ranges and validation
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall provide medically appropriate default ranges for all vital signs: heart rate (60-100 bpm), blood pressure (90/60-140/90 mmHg), O2 saturation (95-100%), respiration rate (12-20 breaths/min). The system shall validate that all defined ranges are within medically safe limits.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model shows methods for defining vital ranges, but requirements don't specify default values or validation rules, which could result in unsafe monitoring parameters being set.

missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall detect loss of network connectivity to hospital LAN and display connection status on LCD. When disconnected, the system shall queue data updates locally and transmit all queued data when connectivity is restored.
missing_requirements.rationale: The system connects to hospital LAN and sends data to external systems, but there are no requirements for handling network failures, which could result in data loss or monitoring interruption.

missing_requirements.description: Vital signs data structure and validation
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall validate all vital sign measurements against physiologically possible ranges (heart rate: 0-300 bpm, blood pressure: 0-300 mmHg, O2 saturation: 0-100%, respiration rate: 0-60 breaths/min) and reject invalid readings. The system shall display data validation errors to users.
missing_requirements.rationale: The Patient class has a vitals attribute and pods record data, but there are no requirements for validating data quality or handling invalid measurements, which could lead to displaying incorrect patient information.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall connect to the hospital LAN via an Ethernet connection when attached to the dock.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall connect to the hospital LAN via an Ethernet connection when attached to the dock. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Connection established within 30 seconds of dock attachment, (2) Network connectivity verified through ping test, (3) Connection remains stable during operation. Dependencies: REQ-038 (docking station power connection).
requirement_completeness.rationale: Missing specific acceptance criteria for verifying successful connection and network performance requirements. Dependencies on docking station functionality should be explicit.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall display heart rate.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall continuously display the current heart rate on the LCD screen with updates every second when vital data is available from connected pods. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Heart rate displayed in beats per minute (BPM), (2) Display updates within 1 second of new data, (3) Shows '--' when no valid data available, (4) Range validation 0-300 BPM.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Missing critical details about display timing, format, update frequency, and validation criteria. No condition specified for when display should occur.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall trigger alarms when the patient's vitals are outside the range that hospital personnel defined.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall trigger visual and audible alarms within 5 seconds when any patient vital sign exceeds the ranges defined by hospital personnel. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Alarm triggered within 5 seconds of threshold breach, (2) Both visual and audible alerts activated, (3) Alarm persists until vital returns to normal range or manually acknowledged. Dependencies: REQ-016, REQ-017, REQ-018, REQ-019 (range definition requirements).
requirement_completeness.rationale: Missing response time requirements, specific dependencies on range definition requirements, and detailed acceptance criteria for alarm behavior.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The LCD screen shall show the EGG strip in a green color (using hexadecimal color code: \#00FF00).
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The LCD screen shall show the ECG strip in a green color (using hexadecimal color code: #00FF00) when ECG data is available from connected telemetry pods. Acceptance Criteria: (1) ECG waveform displayed in specified green color, (2) Color accuracy verified using colorimeter, (3) Waveform updates in real-time with incoming data.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Contains typo 'EGG' instead of 'ECG'. Missing condition for when display should occur and specific acceptance criteria for color accuracy verification.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall make an audible noise that is between 50 and 60 decibels when an alarm is triggered.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall make an audible noise that is between 50 and 60 decibels when an alarm is triggered, measured at 1 meter distance in typical hospital ambient noise conditions. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Sound level measured between 50-60 dB at 1m distance, (2) Sound duration minimum 3 seconds, (3) Sound pattern distinguishable from other equipment, (4) Verification using calibrated sound level meter. Dependencies: REQ-020 (alarm triggering).
requirement_completeness.rationale: Has quality attributes but missing measurement conditions, duration, and verification methods. Dependencies on alarm triggering requirements should be explicit.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall have a two-hour battery life.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall have a minimum two-hour battery life when operating all monitoring functions at normal usage patterns without external power connection. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Battery sustains full operation for minimum 120 minutes, (2) Tested under standard monitoring load (all pods connected and actively monitoring), (3) Battery level indicator shows accurate remaining time, (4) Low battery warning at 15 minutes remaining.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Missing testing conditions and usage scenarios for battery life measurement. No acceptance criteria for battery monitoring and warning systems.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall be compatible with Epic EMR.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall be compatible with Epic EMR system through HL7 FHIR R4 interface for bidirectional data exchange of patient vital signs and demographic information. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Successfully send patient data to Epic using HL7 FHIR R4 format, (2) Receive patient demographics from Epic, (3) Data mapping verified for all vital sign types, (4) Interface tested with Epic certification environment.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Vague compatibility requirement without specifying integration method, data formats, or verification criteria. Missing technical details about how compatibility is achieved.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall be compliant with NFPA standards.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall be compliant with NFPA 99 (Health Care Facilities Code) and NFPA 70 (National Electrical Code) standards for medical electrical equipment used in patient care areas. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Third-party certification of compliance with specified NFPA standards, (2) Documentation of compliance testing results, (3) Installation meets NFPA requirements for patient care equipment.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Too vague - doesn't specify which NFPA standards or how compliance will be verified. Medical equipment should reference specific NFPA codes like NFPA 99.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall be compliant with HIPAA Security Rule (OCR 2022).
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall be compliant with HIPAA Security Rule (45 CFR 164.300-318) as published by OCR 2022, implementing required administrative, physical, and technical safeguards for electronic protected health information (ePHI). Acceptance Criteria: (1) Implementation of all required HIPAA Security Rule safeguards, (2) Security risk assessment completed and documented, (3) Data encryption in transit and at rest, (4) Access controls and audit logging implemented, (5) Compliance verified through security assessment.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Better than REQ-049 as it specifies the version, but still lacks specific security controls and verification methods required for HIPAA compliance.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall not receive software updates when connected to a patient.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall not receive or install software updates when actively monitoring a patient (pods connected and collecting vital data) to ensure continuous patient monitoring without interruption. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Update mechanism detects active patient monitoring, (2) Updates are queued until patient monitoring ends, (3) Update blocking confirmed through testing with connected pods, (4) Manual override available for critical security updates with appropriate warnings.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Missing definition of what constitutes 'connected to a patient' and acceptance criteria for detecting this state. No consideration for emergency update scenarios.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The patient-monitoring system's ethernet connection shall be capable of 100 Mbps while connected to the dock.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The patient-monitoring system's ethernet connection shall be capable of 100 Mbps data transfer rate while connected to the dock, tested under normal hospital network conditions with typical data loads. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Ethernet interface supports 100 Mbps auto-negotiation, (2) Sustained data transfer rate of minimum 95 Mbps measured using network testing tools, (3) Performance maintained during concurrent data streaming to EMR and central monitoring system.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Good requirement with specific quality attributes, but missing testing conditions and acceptance criteria for performance verification under realistic usage scenarios.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The system shall come with documentation containing Battery pack guide to demonstrate how to install and charge the battery.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: The system shall come with printed and digital documentation containing a Battery Pack Installation and Charging Guide with step-by-step instructions, safety warnings, and troubleshooting procedures. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Guide includes illustrated step-by-step installation procedures, (2) Safety warnings and precautions clearly marked, (3) Charging procedures and indicators explained, (4) Troubleshooting section for common issues, (5) Available in English, Spanish, and French per REQ-034, REQ-035.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Vague about documentation format and content requirements. Missing acceptance criteria for content completeness and dependencies on language requirements.
